<br>
It is my belief that when a country's populace decides war is an easy solution, they should be aware that they themselves are open to the effects of war -- not just the people hired to wage war on their behalf.  The United States populace as a whole does not comprehend exactly how devastating a war can be.  It seems surgical, clean, exact, pin-point, quick, and sanitary.  War is none of these things.<br>
<br>
I have no problem with &quot;an enemy combatant&quot;  being killed during the course of armed combat.  Whether they are killed with nerve gas or a high velocity projectile is irrellevant.  Both can be horrible and slow deaths.<br>
<br>
When &quot;an enemy combatant&quot; is taken prisoner and subjected to the laws of a country, then the country with the prisoner has immediately acknowledged the prisoner has rights.  In the United States, the &quot;inalienable rights&quot; is the minimum level of rights are what the &quot;enemy combatant&quot; has been recognized to have.<br>
<br>
By simply trying to validate the removal of these rights, using any court system under the guidance and jurisdiction of the United States (civil, criminal, military), the United States has ACKNODLEGED that the prisoner at one point in time DID have some form of rights to begin with.<br>
<br>
